                        <interp inst="t18330214-64-victim650" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18330214-64-off353 t18330214-64-victim650"></join>
                     </persName>
                     
                  and another
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>PHILOS GISBURNE. I am a <rs id="t18330214-64-viclabel355" type="occupation">bookseller and stationer</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18330214-64-victim650 t18330214-64-viclabel355"></join>, and live in <placeName id="t18330214-64-crimeloc356">Bishopsgate-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18330214-64-crimeloc356" type="placeName" value="Bishopsgate-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18330214-64-crimeloc356" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18330214-64-off353 t18330214-64-crimeloc356"></join>. On Saturday, the 5th of January, about seven o'clock in the evening, the prisoner came and said he came from Mr. Barton, a neighbour, for a small day-book; I told him I had not one of the kind he wished, but would get one made by Monday, at twelve o'clock - he said he would go and see if that would do: he said he was in Mr. Barton's employ; he returned in about five minutes - he produced a small piece of paper, and said twelve o'clock on Monday would do; and he ordered a ledger for Mr. Barton, which was to be done by Monday evening, and he also wished for a Bible and two Prayer-books; he said they were all for Mr. Barton, that Mrs. Barton was waiting in the counting-house for them - I got down some Prayer-books, and was going to send four for Mrs. Barton to chose; he wished to have another, which I gave him, and told him he should have the Bible on the<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183302140040"></xptr>Monday, with the day-book; he said he would return in a short time with the Prayer-books that were not approved of; he did not return that evening - on Monday morning he called for a bill of the Prayer-books; I inquired if Mr. Barton intended to keep the whole of them - he said he would keep the whole if I would take off 2s.; they came to 27s. - I took of 1s. 6d.; he said he dare say that would do, and I made out a bill at his desire, in the name of Mr. Barton; he then said there was some slight difference respecting the account-book, and he wished me not to send them in, but if I would get them both done by the evening, he would call for them; he called in the evening - I suspected it was not correct, and stopped him; he always said they were for Mr. Barton.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18330214-64-person651">
                  WILLIAM 
                  LUDLAM BARTON
               <interp inst="t18330214-64-person651" type="surname" value="LUDLAM BARTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18330214-64-person651" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18330214-64-person651" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live in Bishopsgate-street within. On the 5th of January the prisoner was not in my employ; I never authorised him to call on Mr. Gisburn for any Prayer-books - I have employed him occasionally as a cooper, but never as a servant; I had no occasion for any Prayer-books, nor had any of my family; they were never brought to my house; I heard of this the beginning of January - the prisoner was taken soon after.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. I had the order given me by a person in the street; I gave the books to that person.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18330214-64-verdict357" type="verdictDescription">
